From
\href{Science:Math Exam Resources/Courses/MATH105/April 2010/Question 5 (a)}{part
(a)}, we have

\begin{align*}\frac{dy}{dt} = 0.05y - A,\end{align*}

which we will solve by separation of variables. Knowing the solution
will allow us to give a condition on $A$ so that after 25 years, the
balance owed is zero.

We notice that the equation is separable and rearrange to find

\begin{align*}\frac{dy}{0.05y - A} = dt.\end{align*}

Now we integrate to get

\begin{align*}\int \frac{dy}{0.05y - A} = 20 \ln |0.05 y - A| = t + C.\end{align*}

Therefore,

\begin{align*}
\ln|0.05y - A| &= t/20 + C/20\\
|0.05y - A| &= e^{t/20+C/20} = e^{C/20}e^{t/20}\\
0.05y - A &= F e^{t/20}\end{align*}

where $F$ is an arbitrary constant that comes out of the integration,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
\pm e^{C/20}\end{align*}

in this case.

After one last rearrangement, we see that the amount of money owed after
$t$ years is

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y(t) = 20A + 20Fe^{t/20}\end{align*}

or

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y(t) = 20A + Ge^{20t}\end{align*}

for another arbitary constant $G$.

From the initial condition, $y(0) = 240 000$ so $20A + G = 240 000$ or
$G = 240,000-20A$. Finally then our full equation for the amount of
money owing, $y(t)$ is,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y(t) = (240000-20A)e^{t/20} + 20A.\end{align*}

Setting $y(25) = 0$ (which corresponds to having no money owing after 25
years) forces

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}(240000-20A)e^{25/20} + 20A = 0\end{align*}

so

\begin{align*}A = \frac{240000e^{25/20}}{20(e^{25/20}-1)} = \frac{12000e^{5/4}}{e^{5/4}-1}=16818.61.\end{align*}

Therefore, the annual payments are $A$ = \$16818.61.
